# Tessera tuning configuration
#
# COMMITTED, not gitignored. This template previously said "gitignored by default" — wrong
# for toolchain facts: a test command that vanishes on a fresh clone is useless to the
# unsupervised agent it exists for. Keep secrets out of this file.
#
# ONLY keys that something ACTUALLY READS belong here. A knob that silently does nothing is
# worse than no knob — it grants false assurance. This template used to ship six knobs
# (claude_code_auto_compact_window, bcrypt_rounds, tls_minimum, coverage_threshold, mnemos
# bands, suggestion_gate threshold) and EVERY ONE was dead: read by nothing, designed
# top-down from the design doc rather than from observed pain — while the one key that maps
# to a real failure was missing. Removed 2026-07-11. Someone setting `tls_minimum: "1.3"` and
# believing it was enforced is a security hazard, not a harmless no-op.
# See docs/observatory.md → "The profile model has no consumer".

# --- toolchain (read by bin/tessera-test) ---
#
# The command that runs this project's tests. Declare it so an agent never has to GUESS.
#
# Not hypothetical: bare `python3` can resolve to an interpreter with no pytest — the same
# interpreter split that silently killed the Mnemos hooks (F-001). A human guesses wrong once
# and recovers in a second. An unsupervised agent (ADR-0005) reads "No module named pytest",
# concludes the suite is broken, and acts on it.
#
# ── AN INTERPRETER IS A PATH, NOT A NAME. ───────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# This template used to advise "prefer PATH-relative commands" and offer
# `test: python3.13 -m pytest` as the Python example. **That advice was the bug.** It is where
# conclave's test command came from, and on 2026-07-12 `uv python install` shimmed the name
# `python3.13` into ~/.local/bin — ahead of Homebrew — so it silently became a *different*
# interpreter with no pytest, and conclave's suite broke.
#
# A NAME (`python3`, `python3.13`) is a lookup through a mutable, ordered PATH that several
# package managers write to. Any of them can win, at any time, without telling you.
# A REPO-RELATIVE PATH (`.venv/bin/python`) resolves to one interpreter, forever, on every
# machine. That is the fix — and note it is neither a bare name NOR a machine-absolute path.
#
# Still true: do NOT pin machine-absolute paths like /opt/homebrew/bin/python3.13 — those
# break on every other machine. Repo-relative is the sweet spot.
#
#   python:  test: .venv/bin/python -m pytest      ← a path. build it: uv venv && uv pip install pytest
#   node:    test: npm test                         ← npm resolves node_modules/ locally already
#   kotlin:  test: ./gradlew test                   ← the wrapper IS the path, that is its point
test:
